  "local_port": 46932,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the types of scholarships for international undergraduate students who don\u2019t have concerns with housing?",
  "response": "International undergraduate students have access to various types of scholarships that can help reduce their tuition costs. While housing concerns are not a factor for these scholarships, they can still be categorized in several ways:\n\n1. **Merit-Based Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded based on academic achievement, standardized test scores, or other accomplishments. Many universities offer merit scholarships to attract high-achieving international students.\n\n2. **Need-Based Scholarships**: Although not as common for international students, some institutions provide need-based aid for those who demonstrate financial need. Students may need to submit financial information to be considered.\n\n3. **Country-Specific Scholarships**: Some universities or organizations offer scholarships specifically for students from certain countries to promote diversity. These can be based on bilateral agreements or to encourage students from developing nations.\n\n4. **Program-Specific Scholarships**: Certain academic programs may have dedicated scholarships for international students, especially in fields like STEM, Arts, or Business. These scholarships target specific disciplines or areas of study.\n\n5. **Diversity Scholarships**: Some institutions offer scholarships aimed at promoting diversity within their student body. These scholarships often consider cultural background, ethnicity, or underrepresented groups in higher education.\n\n6. **Athletic Scholarships**: Talented student-athletes may receive scholarships based on their athletic abilities. These are typically offered by universities with competitive sports programs and may require the student to compete at the collegiate level.\n\n7. **Institutional Scholarships**: Many universities have their own scholarship programs funded by donations or endowments. These can vary greatly in amount and criteria, so it's essential to check individual university offerings.\n\n8. **International Student Scholarships**: Some organizations and foundations specifically offer scholarships for international students. These may have varying eligibility criteria and application processes.\n\n9. **Research/Assistantship Scholarships**: In some cases, international undergraduate students can apply for research positions or teaching assistantships that come with tuition waivers or stipends.\n\n10. **Government or Non-Governmental Scholarships**: Some international students may be eligible for scholarships funded by their home countries, foreign governments, or non-governmental organizations that support education abroad.\n\n11. **Rotary or Lions Club Scholarships**: Local or international service organizations may offer scholarships for international students as part of their community service or educational outreach programs.\n\nIn general, students interested in applying for scholarships should carefully research the opportunities available at their target institutions and consider external scholarships that may fit their backgrounds and interests.",
